"Vitale M., Scimone M., Feoli E., Manes F.","Modelling leaf gas exchanges to predict functional trends in Mediterranean Quercus Ilex forest under climatic changes in temperature",2003,"Ecological Modelling","166","1-2",,"123","134",,,10.1016/S0304-3800(03)00129-7,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0346816521&partnerID=40&md5=7a95f3008135a342090414877583243c","Dipartimento di Biologia Vegetale, Università La Sapienza, P.le A. Moro, 5, I-00I85 Roma, Italy; SISSAD snc, Viale Campi Elisi, 62, I-34100 Trieste, Italy; Dipartimento di Biologia, Università di Trieste, Via Giorgieri 10, I-34100 Trieste, Italy","Vitale, M., Dipartimento di Biologia Vegetale, Università La Sapienza, P.le A. Moro, 5, I-00I85 Roma, Italy; Scimone, M., SISSAD snc, Viale Campi Elisi, 62, I-34100 Trieste, Italy; Feoli, E., Dipartimento di Biologia, Università di Trieste, Via Giorgieri 10, I-34100 Trieste, Italy; Manes, F., Dipartimento di Biologia Vegetale, Università La Sapienza, P.le A. Moro, 5, I-00I85 Roma, Italy","A simple model based on the ""big leaf"" assumption and calibrated with field eco-physiological measures of gas exchanges is used to simulate the effects of temperature increase on net primary production, total canopy transpiration and the dimensionless decoupling coefficient Ω of Holm oak forests. Two different annual average air temperatures: 14.6 and 18.0°C are considered, they are respectively the average current temperature and the one expected in the next 50 years in the Mediterranean area if the trend of global warming will continue. The model simulates the behaviour of the three parameters by assuming no changes in the effects of water constraints at both the temperatures. The model has been implemented by STELLA® II software. According to the model, the increase of air temperature affects both the net primary productivity (6.3%) and the water losses by canopy transpiration (37.2%). The model predicts an average decoupling factor, Ω, of about 0. 26 at both temperatures of 14.6 and 18.0°C. This value is in the range between Heathlands and Forest, suggesting that at the average annual temperature of 18.0°C the Holm oak forest will start to respond in a similar way to more xeric plant communities. © 2003 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Decoupling coefficient; Holm oak; Mediterranean area; Modelling; Photosynthesis; Primary production; Transpiration","climate change; ecological modeling; gas exchange; photosynthesis; primary production; temperature; transpiration; Mediterranean Region; Mediterranean Sea; Ilex; Quercus; Quercus ilex",,,,,,"Ågren, G.I., McMurtrie, R.E., Parton, W.J., Pastor, J., Shugart, H.H., State-of-the-art of model of production-decomposition linkages in conifer and grassland ecosystems (1991) Ecol. Appl., 1, pp. 118-138; Amthor, J.S., Goulden, M.L., Munger, J.W., Wofsy, S.C., Testing a mechanistic model of forest-canopy mass and energy exchange using eddy correlation: Carbon dioxide and ozone uptake by a mixed oak-maple stand (1994) Aust. J. Plant Physiol., 21, pp. 623-651; Anselmi, B., Blasi, L., Brandimarte, U., Brondi, M., Bucci, M., Caprioli, R., Cautilli, F., Vincenzi, D., (1995) Studi Idrogeologici e Monitoraggio Delle Falde. Progetto di Monitoraggio Ambientale Della Tenuta Presidenziale di Castelporziano, pp. 98-110. , Second Report, May 12, 1995; Baldocchi, D., Falge, E., Gu, L., Olson, R., Hollinger, D., Running, S., Anthoni, P., Wofsy, S., FLUXNET: A new tool to study the temporal and spatial variability of ecosystem-scale carbon dioxide, water vapor, and energy flux densities (2001) Bull. Am. Meteorol. Soc., 82 (11), pp. 2415-2434; Ball, J.T., Woodrow, I.E., Berry, J.A., A model predicting stomatal conductance and its contribution to the control of photosynthesis under different environmental conditions (1987) Progress in Photosynthesis Research, 4, pp. IV5221-IV5224. , Biggins, J. (Ed.); Björn, L.O., Vogelmann, T.C., Quantification of light (1993) Photomorphogenesis in Plants, 2nd Ed., p